thread.title: Coach sees early playing opportunity at Auburn for quarterback commit Woody Barrett
thread.title_full: Coach sees early playing opportunity at Auburn for quarterback commit Woody Barrett

author: Drew Champlin | dchamplin@al.com
title: Coach sees early playing opportunity at Auburn for quarterback commit Woody Barrett
text:
Comments 
It was no big surprise to West Orange head coach Bob Head that his team, led by star quarterback Woody Barrett , was able to bounce back from its first loss last week. 
Barrett had 16 carries for 160 yards and two touchdowns and threw for 78 yards and a score in a 28-3 win over defending 8A state champion Apopka, avenging a loss from the week before. 
The Auburn commit, rated as a four-star recruit, has put up similar lines all season for his team while playing a tough schedule in the Orlando area. 
Some highlights include passing for 178 and rushing for 128 in a 45-0 win over Foundation and in West Orange's other huge win, when ran for 217 yards and three scores and threw for 142 yards and two touchdowns in a 41-34 win to snap Dr. Phillips' 35-game win streak . 
"Every win we have, it's Woody Barrett," Head said. "I'm loving it. He's playing hard. He's making great reads. He's leading the entire county in rushing. I think he's well over 700 tough yards rushing. He's really done a great job." 
While Auburn's offense has sputtered, Barrett remains firm in his commitment, according to Head. Gus Malzahn's offense has flourished with better runners, and the 6-foot-2, 225-pound Barrett has shown the ability to be a true dual-threat quarterback. 
"He's tons, light years better as a passer," Head said. "He's dissecting defenses and really making reads. He's really doing a great job." 
Barrett plans on graduating from high school early to enroll at Auburn in January 2016. Auburn coaches feel he can challenge for early playing time. 
"That's what they're saying and that's what they're telling me," Head said. "That's what I'm seeing." 
Barrett did make the short trip to Gainesville to watch Florida's 38-10 win over Ole Miss, but told 247Sports that it was more of a trip just to hang out. Florida has not extended an offer. 
In fact, other schools haven't been in much contact, according to Head. 
"Not at all, but I haven't really been allowing much of that right now," Head said. "Until he tells me he's not strong with (his commitment), we'll just keep it all in house right now." 
Barrett visited Auburn over the summer and Head said he's hoping to make it for a game, but it's around a six or seven-hour drive from Winter Garden, Fla., to Auburn.
